    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a fascinating concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are.  If you measure a property of one entangled particle—say, its spin—you instantly know the corresponding property of the other particle, even if it's across the galaxy.  The key difference from classical correlation is that this connection isn't due to any pre-arranged instructions or hidden variables, which is what you might expect from, say, two matching socks you put in separate boxes. It's a genuine, spooky connection, as Einstein famously called it.",
